## 5. Shape vs Vega/Vega-Lite, and the justified divergences

The manifest is intentionally **Vega-Lite-shaped** (data → transform → scale → mark/encoding) so the AI's pretraining transfers, and so ~70% of the chart universe (CHART-UNIVERSE) reduces to composable manifests just as it does in Vega. Five deliberate divergences, each forced by GPU-native + streaming:

| # | Divergence | Vega/VL | DynaCharting manifest | Justification |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Streaming class + cadence on every transform** | VL has *no* native streaming primitive; compiles to Vega's reactive dataflow (CPU) | each transform declares `stream.class ∈ {incremental,windowed,globalRecompute,iterative,illDefined}` + `cadence` | engine must schedule class-1 per-frame, class-3 on debounce (STREAMING); running the transform DAG as per-frame GPU passes is done by *no* prior-art system |
| 2 | **Explicit pipeline/format binding per mark** | VL marks are format-agnostic; renderer picks | `"pipeline":"instancedCandle@1"` + format-coverage check | the engine hard-rejects geometry ≠ pipeline format (`validateDrawItem`); the manifest must commit to a GPU target so the compiler can pack the exact vertex/instance stride |
| 3 | **Auto-domain *with streaming policy*** | VL auto-domains statically over a fixed dataset | every scale has `autodomain.stream ∈ {fixed,extend,decay,window}` | domains drift every tick; class-4 transforms are ill-defined without a declared baseline (STREAMING) — the policy is first-class, not implicit |
| 4 | **First-class `coords` block (affine/polar/geo/projection)** | VL folds coordinate systems into mark config; arbitrary projection needs a `coord_*`/Vega projection | `coords:{cartesian|polar|geo{projection}|affineFree}` replaces the engine's single baked affine mat3 | the baked mat3 is affine-only (no rotation/shear/projection); polar (radial charts) and geo (choropleth) need named coordinate-transform primitives the affine stage lacks (CHART-UNIVERSE #4) |
| 5 | **Typed `customCompute` WGSL escape hatch** | Vega escapes via JS custom transforms (a *restricted-JS* expression lang with no iteration); VL escapes by compiling to Vega | `compute:{backend:"wgsl", passes, io, wgsl}` with Tint validation + declared IO bindings | the walled tail (KDE/FFT/marching-squares/force/treemap) is genuinely outside any declarative grammar (PRIOR-ART: no grammar has FFT/spectral; 3D/streamline absent); like *every* prior-art system we need an escape hatch, but ours targets GPU compute and is typed/sandboxed rather than arbitrary host JS |

**Where we converge (and should not reinvent):** mark vocabulary (point/line/area/rect/rule/arc/text — Vega's irreducible ~9 minus geo/image as coords concerns), scale vocabulary (~13, identical to Vega/D3), and the basic transform set (filter/formula/bin/aggregate/stack/sort/window — Vega's "basic" tier). These are the proven, stable basis; the divergences are precisely the streaming-GPU concerns Vega-Lite never had to solve.

**Honest limit:** the named heavyweight transforms (`treemap`, `force`, `contour`, `voronoi`, `geoproject`, `fft`, `kde`) are *not* derivable from the basic transform algebra — they are engine-implemented primitives the manifest merely *invokes*. So the manifest format is universal **iff** the engine ships those primitives or the author drops to `customCompute`. The manifest grammar covers the composed middle declaratively and walls the tail behind named primitives + one typed escape hatch — exactly the structure every prior-art grammar converged on, now made GPU-native and streaming.
